<DOC><DOCNO> AP880227-0076 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-88 1130EST</FILEID><FIRST>d a AM-BRF--PlazaHotel     02-27 0160</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Plaza Hotel,0163</SECOND><HEAD>Newspaper Says Plaza Hotel Could Be Converted To Co-op</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The elegant Plaza Hotel, the Fifth Avenuebastion of luxury overlooking Central Park, might be sold withinweeks and a portion of it could be converted to cooperativeapartments, a newspaper reported Saturday.   The 18-story hotel offers rooms from $195 a night for a singleto $800 for a suite.   Real estate dealers Philip Pilevsky and Arthur G. Cohen saidthey were close to a $400 million to $500 million agreement to buythe hotel, The New York Times reported.   It said the two have formed a joint venture with the MandarinOriental Hotel Group of Hong Kong, which owns luxury hotels on bothsides of the Pacific, to buy the Plaza from the Bass family of FortWorth, Texas.   Pilevsky said the style and spirit of the hotel would remain,but part of it would be converted to cooperative ownership afterrenovations.</TEXT></DOC>